\section{Main Body}
This is the main body of the document.

\subsection{Section 1}
This is section 1 of the main body.

\subsection{Section 2}
This is section 2 of the main body.

% Add the conclusion section
\section{Conclusion}
This is the conclusion section.

% This command is used to update the table of contents
\clearpage
\tableofcontents

\end{document}
```

However, it's important to note that you need to compile the document multiple times for the table of contents to be generated properly. The first time you compile, LaTeX will create the necessary references. The second time you compile, LaTeX will use those references to create the table of contents.

In the example above, the \tableofcontents command is used to generate the table of contents, and the \section and \subsection commands are used to create the headings and subheadings that will be included in the table of contents. The \clearpage command is used to ensure that all pages are properly flushed before the table of contents is generated again.

However, if you're using the hyperref package for creating hyperlinks within your document, you should place the \tableofcontents command after \begin{document} and before any sections, instead of using the clearpage and the second \tableofcontents as I did in the example. Here's how you can do it:

```latex
